<p>The <code>ajax</code> tag handles AJAX requests.</p>

<h2>Syntax</h2>
<pre>{open}ajax 'handler_name'{close}</pre>

<h2>What Is AJAX?</h2>
<p>AJAX (Asynchronous JavaScript and XML) allows web pages to update content without reloading. The ajax tag provides server-side handling for these requests.</p>

<h2>How It Works</h2>
<ol>
  <li>Client sends AJAX request to PAD endpoint</li>
  <li>PAD detects the AJAX request</li>
  <li>The ajax tag processes the request</li>
  <li>Response is returned to client</li>
</ol>

<h2>Example Handler</h2>
<pre>{open}ajax 'getData'{close}</pre>
<p>This would handle an AJAX request using the 'getData' handler.</p>

<h2>Client-Side Request</h2>
<pre>&lt;script&gt;
fetch('?ajax=getData')
  .then(response =&gt; response.json())
  .then(data =&gt; console.log(data));
&lt;/script&gt;</pre>

<h2>Use Cases</h2>
<ul>
  <li>Dynamic content loading</li>
  <li>Form submission without page reload</li>
  <li>Real-time data updates</li>
  <li>Search suggestions</li>
  <li>Infinite scrolling</li>
</ul>

<h2>Response Format</h2>
<p>AJAX handlers typically return JSON data for client-side processing.</p>

<h2>Note</h2>
<p>The ajax tag handles the server-side of AJAX communication. You'll need corresponding JavaScript on the client side to make the requests.</p>
